2026-05-17 05:43:14 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #4 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_ideal({"intent": "Identify the northernmost Neolithic Homo sapiens sample year in radiocarbon_database_regional.xlsx (tie -> later calendar year), then find maximum climate dataset Al in the closest climate year(s) to that year.", "dataset_id": "kramabench-archeology-hard-5", "code": "import pandas as pd, numpy as np\n\nrad_path = DOWNLOAD_PATHS[\"kramabench-archeology-hard-5/files/radiocarbon_database_regional.xlsx\"]\ncli_path = DOWNLOAD_PATHS[\"kramabench-archeology-hard-5/files/climateMeasurements.xlsx\"]\n\n# Load radiocarbon workbook\nrad = pd.read_excel(rad_path, sheet_name=0)\n\n# Filter Homo sapiens + Neolithic\n# Culture column holds \"Neolithic\" / \"Mesolithic\" etc.\nrad_hs_neol = rad[(rad['Species'].astype(str).str.strip()=='Homo sapiens') & (rad['Culture'].astype(str).str.contains('Neolithic', na=False))].copy()\n\n# Determine available calendar year column(s)\n# Prefer Cal. BC 1 sigma range lower/upper bounds. The dataset uses a string like '7020- 6323'\n# We'll parse max value from the range by taking the later calendar year (less BC -> closer to present).\ncal1 = 'Cal. BC 1 sigma'\ncal2 = 'Cal. BC 2 sigma'\n\n# Parse latitude\nrad_hs_neol['Latitude'] = pd.to_numeric(rad_hs_neol['Latitude'], errors='coerce')\n\n# Parse later year from Cal. BC 1 sigma range\ndef later_from_range(x):\n    if pd.isna(x):\n        return np.nan\n    s=str(x)\n    # extract two numbers\n    import re\n    nums = re.findall(r'\\d+(?:\\.\\d+)?', s.replace(',', '.'))\n    if len(nums)<2:\n        return np.nan\n    a=float(nums[0]); b=float(nums[1])\n    # For Cal BC, larger number is older; later calendar year means smaller BC value\n    return min(a,b)\n\n# Use later year for tie-breaking\nrad_hs_neol['CalLaterBC'] = rad_hs_neol[cal1].apply(later_from_range)\n\n# If still missing, try Cal. BC 2 sigma\nmask = rad_hs_neol['CalLaterBC'].isna()\nrad_hs_neol.loc[mask,'CalLaterBC'] = rad_hs_neol.loc[mask,cal2].apply(later_from_range)\n\n# Northernmost: max latitude; tie break by later calendar year (larger? For BC, later=smaller BC)\n# We'll pick later by sorting CalLaterBC ascending (smaller BC -> later)\nrad_hs_neol = rad_hs_neol.dropna(subset=['Latitude','CalLaterBC'])\n\n# For robustness, if multiple samples share max latitude, choose with smallest CalLaterBC\nmax_lat = rad_hs_neol['Latitude'].max()\ncand = rad_hs_neol[rad_hs_neol['Latitude']==max_lat]\n# later year => smallest BC\nsel = cand.sort_values('CalLaterBC', ascending=True).iloc[0]\nselected_year_bc = sel['CalLaterBC']\n\n# Convert BC year to CE-like? Climate likely uses Age_ky forward in thousands years ago.\n# We'll match by climate 'Age_ky' converted to years BP? Need closest year to that year.\n\ncli = pd.read_excel(cli_path, sheet_name=0)\n\n# Climate dataset has columns Age_ky and Al, possibly more. We need closest year to selected_year_bc.\n# Interpret selected_year_bc as calendar year BC. Convert to years before present (BP) as: yearBP = selected_year_bc + 1950\n# Since climate Age_ky likely in thousands of years ago relative to present.\n# We'll compute target age_ky = (selected_year_bc + 1950)/1000.\n\ntarget_age_ky = (selected_year_bc + 1950)/1000.0\n\ncli['Age_ky'] = pd.to_numeric(cli['Age_ky'], errors='coerce')\ncli['Al'] = pd.to_numeric(cli['Al'], errors='coerce')\ncli = cli.dropna(subset=['Age_ky','Al'])\n\n# Find closest climate Age_ky value(s)\nmin_diff = (cli['Age_ky']-target_age_ky).abs().min()\nclosest = cli[(cli['Age_ky']-target_age_ky).abs()==min_diff]\nmax_al = closest['Al'].max()\n\nans = round(float(max_al),4)\nprint(\"selected_year_bc\", selected_year_bc)\nprint(\"target_age_ky\", target_age_ky)\nprint(\"min_diff\", min_diff)\nprint(\"max_al\", ans)\nprint(ans)\n"}) [toolUseId=call_Uzu7w2Po6AikycZt4wPmIG9r]
